There’s 2 parts to the banded joint mobilization. Let’s go over them.👇🏼
.
First, push the knee across the body while you RELAX the hip muscles. This is pushing into hip internal rotation. Now If this creates a pinch/block sensation in the front of the hip - get more tension on the band. Hold for a few seconds - you may get a light gapping sensation in your lateral hip. 
.
Second, push the knee out to the side and squeeze your glutes. This is driving active external rotation and re-educating your body to create this optimal lateral and posterior glute engagement during your lifts. Hold for a few seconds again.
.
Usually I have athletes/patients do 5-10 reps and then ALWAYS retest your squat to see how you’re moving after & assess whether this was a good exercise for you. 
.
As always, shout out to Dr. Kelly Starrett of @thereadystate from whom I first learned these from! 
.
Knowledge is power - tag a friend in the comments below who needs to try these!

When most see the knees shifting during a squat they’ll jump in and yell “knees wide”! But what happens when that doesn’t work?🤔
.
While corrective exercises that focus on improving stability can definitely be helpful, let's not forget about just slowing down the problem movement and focusing on FEELING the lift and when the problem occurs. Tempo work can be a game-changer for solidifying control of a movement. This slow descent squat for enhancing awareness of your positioning is a tip I first learned from the greatest powerlifter of all time @eddycoan 
.

node.text:
When we talk about how to perform a great looking squat, we often discuss things like keeping your knees in line with stable feet and a balanced descent into the bottom – but what most don’t discuss is the importance of the start position. 
.
When I refer to the start position, I’m talking about the quality of your posture standing with the barbell on your back and the actions you take before you start the descent. 
.
For example, when you take the bar out of the rack, I often see many athletes incorrectly shrug up on the bar. This places a lot of excessive pressure on your neck and makes it difficult to stabilize the bar when you start getting fatigued. Instead, pull your shoulder blades together and down as you wedge yourself against the bar. 
.
So instead of having a ton of over – activity in your upper traps, we want to focus in on creating as much stiffness and muscle contraction in the mid and low trap and lats. 
.
By doing this correctly, you will create a nice shelf for the barbell to sit on as you walk the bar back out of the rack. Once you get your stance set, take a huge breath and brace your core. You can see Lee’s stomach expand into his belt as he takes inhales before slowly starting his squat by hinging his hips back and only then going into his descent. 
.
By solidifying stiffness and stability in your start position, you set yourself up for a more efficient squat pattern.🙌🏼
.

In order for the hips to sink deep when you squat, you need the knees to translate forward towards the toes – this requires sufficient ankle mobility. The joint connection of the talus bone and tibia must move unrestricted and the muscles on the backside of the calf (like the larger gastric and smaller soleus) must be flexible enough to allow your shin to move forward.
.
To test this mobility, I had him try the 5” wall test – and as you can see he was unable to hit the wall with his knee without his heel popping off the ground – illuminating his problem!
.
I recommended he start with these 3 ankle mobility drills: 20 reps of a banded joint mobilizations with the band placed on top of the talus bone just under the larger ankle bones holding the end position for 3 seconds before coming back. Then 3 sets of 30 seconds on a box calf stretch – driving the knee over the toes until it brings out a good stretch in the back of the calf/achilles tendon area. He followed this with a deep goblet squat stretch, swiveling one knee at a time over the toes until a good stretch is found in the back of the calf again. This is a great “position specific” stretch as it works to improve ankle mobility in a deep squat position we’re trying to improve. .
After adding these into his warm up he noted an ability to squat deeper as you can see and felt more comfortable in his bottom position with weight on his back. Here’s a before and after with similar weight. Great work Jared!
.

Don’t fear flexion, understand it. Let’s talk about context.
.
If we look deep in your spine each disc has an inner nucleus that is surrounded by layers of collagen rings held together by a ground substance✅
.
Gymnasts focus a lot of their core work with exercises that move the spine through full ranges. Because there is low amounts of load with spinal movement, their spines stay flexible and resilient to safely handle skill work that requires forced end range of flexion.🤸🏼‍♀️
.
In order for powerlifters to lift massive weights and maintain the integrity of the spine, the spine must be held stable. This stiffness allows for resiliency with high loads. For this reason, strength athletes should perform isometric core exercises with the goal to resist excessive movement.✅
.
If the powerlifter trained like the gymnast, allowing the back to round under load over and over again, they weaken disc structure, increasing risk of a disc bulge  as the nucleus becomes pressurized under compression and works its ways through cracks in the rings.❌Does this mean everyone who rounds their back in a deadlift instantly is going to get a disc bulge? No, but the risk is increased the more load and the more reps someone performs.📝
.
So when someone asks, is all spinal flexion dangerous? Say, "it depends." Is the spine loaded and what is the end goal of what the person is trying to build.✅
.

The stretch I'm demonstrating today is one of my favorite hip openers to use prior to squatting. It's a stretch I learned years ago from Kelly Starrett of @thereadystate. Keys for proper execution: keep your trail leg straight & lean from the hips (don't drop your chest as you lean forward). As always, test - retest to see if this mobility exercise is right for you! Sit into a deep squat. Notice how you feel. Then perform this stretch - and immediately sit into your squat after. If you felt like you could sit more comfortably in the deep squat position - this stretch was efficient for your body to help you get into better positions! 
.
To learn more of my other favorite hip mobility exercises, check out my YouTube video “Hip Mobility for a Perfect Squat.”📲
.

node.text:
Did you know the Spanish Squat can be both a first line of treatment AND a useful diagnostic tool for patellar and quad tendon injuries?🤯
.
These injuries occur when the current loading of your program exceeds your current strength tolerance level of your tendons. If the injury isn’t dealt with properly and the athlete continues to push through pain, small portions of the tendon tissue actually die off in a process called “degeneration.” Think of the islands of degenerated patellar or quad tendon fibers as holes in a donut that are surrounded by healthy tissue.📝
.
The Spanish squat (performed for 5 repetitions of 45 seconds) has been shown in research to to reduce pain for tendinopathy upwards of 45 minutes after performing and also spark the ability of the quad to kick back on, as it is usually inhibited in strength output due to pain (called cortical inhibition).📝
.
If performing these exercises do not decrease pain thereafter and instead increase your knee symptoms, you likely are dealing with a different type of knee injury (called Patellofemoral pain)🥊
.
If you are dealing with a tendinopathy, the next steps would then be performing slow tempo box squats & eventually returning to more plyometric movements like depth drops and jumps.✅
.
To learn more about rehab from a patellar or quad tendon injury, check out the blog article “How to fix patellar and quad Tendonitis”.📲
.

node.text:
Here’s some ideas for a recovery day or week from training. You see in order to progress your training you need periods of recovery for your body to bounce back and adapt. This idea of managing intensity of volume of loading can be as simple as having lighter days and weeks within a program in order to allow for optimal adaptation over time. Train too heavy too often and you won’t see the progress you want as your body will fail to adapt. Sometimes we need a few days to a full week of recovery between intense months of training to allow our body to heal from training. Again the idea is to stress the body just enough but not too much so that we can adapt, recover and continue our quest towards improved performance. 
.
Big shout out to @olychad who is MY coach & does my programming (remember even coaches need coaches😉).

Tip #2: Next make sure you are creating a straight line from your heel to shoulder of your free leg – as doing so will enhance your posterior chain activation of your stance leg.

Do you perform the classic front plank as a core stability exercise? While there’s nothing wrong with it, if you think about it there’s not many lifts in the weight room where your entire body is held in a constant stiff position. We try to maintain a stiff braced low back while there is always movement occurring at the hips and/or arms.🏋🏼‍♀️
.
To make the classic front plank that much more efficient, do it off a small ball. Once in your plank position, move the ball forward and back, side to side or even around in small circles. Doing so will effectively target your core muscles like your transverse abdominus or TA, rectus abdominus or 6-pack muscles, as well as your internal and external obliques as they have to kick on to limit motion In a number of different directions. We work these muscles NOT for the sake of isolation building but teaching them how to work to limit spinal movement!
.
The ability to move the arms, while maintaining a neutral braced spine will carry over more efficiently than the classic plank to the way in which you move in the weight room and in life – like we see here with the barbell press.✅
.
Remember, true core stability isn’t just the ability to maintain a position for a long time, but the ability to limit excessive movement at the low back while movement occurs elsewhere in the body.🙌🏼
.
Shout out to @olychad & @lee_sang____ for their lifting videos featured today & @3d4medical with the Complete Anatomy app for the visual of the body🙏🏼

There’s 2 parts to the banded joint mobilization. Let’s go over them.👇🏼
.
First, push the knee across the body while you RELAX the hip muscles. This is pushing into hip internal rotation. Now If this creates a pinch/block sensation in the front of the hip - get more tension on the band. Hold for a few seconds - you may get a light gapping sensation in your lateral hip. 
.
Second, push the knee out to the side and squeeze your glutes. This is driving active external rotation and re-educating your body to create this optimal lateral and posterior glute engagement during your lifts. Hold for a few seconds again.
.
Usually I have athletes/patients do 5-10 reps and then ALWAYS retest your squat to see how you’re moving after & assess whether this was a good exercise for you. 
.
As always, shout out to Dr. Kelly Starrett of @thereadystate from whom I first learned these from! 
.
Knowledge is power - tag a friend in the comments below who needs to try these!

What are you favorite “core” exercises? I’ve said many times “any lift is technically a core exercise if done properly.” Within this conversation there is always a time/place for assistant work in an athletes training program.
.
The goal of any assistant work is to “assist” the main goals of the program. If we’re trying to get as much return on investment with this area of lifting AND have as much carry over to or end goals - it would make sense that we want our “core” work to be aimed at helping athletes move better rather than try to “build a 6 pack.” Doing a bunch of crunches or side bends isn’t going to help you maintain proper technique in terms of back posture & positioning during a heavy deadlift or clean & jerk for example. 
.
I’m not trying to demonize traditional isolation ab exercises but rather trying to make you think about each and every exercise you do. Many ripped athletes in the sport of weightlifting for example are NOT spending a ton of their time doing sit ups. Their musculature development is a by-product of optimal training & proper nutrition.
.
This is a big reason why bodybuilding is a very different sport than powerlifting or weightlifting. Sure both can utilize lifts like squats and deadlifts but the bodybuilder is working to sculpt their body for their show where as a powerlifter or weightlifter needs to lift heavy. We’ve all seen athletes who are extremely ripped fail to move the barbell well - and it all comes down to “why.” Are you making the most optimal choices for your goals?
